WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.000
So, today I will be talking about clustering in tidymodels. It's something I've been working

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:22.400
with Kelly Bartwin with for the last half year or so, and I'm very excited to come here

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:29.320
and talk to all of you about it. So, before we get any further, I want to give a quick

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:37.000
additional introduction to what I find most important about tidymodels as a framework.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:44.160
And the three most important things I see is that it's consistent, modular, and extensible.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:48.720
It's consistent in a way that any function that returns a tuple will always return a

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:54.320
tuple. If you return a fitted object, it's always a fitted object. And any things like

00:00:54.320 --> 00:01:02.439
dimensions with respect to column names and row numbers will always stay the same. So

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:08.440
once you know what a function outputs, you can reliably code knowing that that will be

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:17.639
the case. Secondly, it's modular in the sense that instead of having one monster function

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:23.400
that will do a bunch of preprocessing, fit a model inside a cross-variation fold, and

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:31.120
find the most optimal model according to some heuristic, we instead create smaller objects

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:41.800
that we can then bind together. Allows us to easily swap out and build a more complete

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:52.839
workflow. And lastly, and for me most importantly, is the idea of extensibility. So, tidymodels

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:59.919
was built from the ground up knowing that we needed to make it so other people could

00:01:59.919 --> 00:02:10.199
build extensions and to make it much more maintainable. Instead of having one large

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:15.039
package with hundreds of thousands of code that needs to all be kept in sync, instead

00:02:15.039 --> 00:02:21.559
we have smaller, more focused packages that can be handled independently, yet they all

00:02:21.559 --> 00:02:28.279
still work wonderfully together. This part is near and dear to my heart because this

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:33.440
is how I started working with tidymodels four years ago when I started working on my first

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:40.960
extension package. And now it led me up here to talk about another extension package in

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:49.240
front of all of you. So, when we think about machine learning, it's a wonderfully ill-defined

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:58.479
topic, but one of the ways we can think about it is in the idea of unsupervised and a supervised

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:07.320
setting. So, tidymodels right now works really well in the supervised setting. We can do

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:13.679
classification, we can do regression. As we just saw, we also are starting to work on

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:20.839
tools to deal with sensor regression, which isn't even on this diagram. We also have tools

00:03:20.839 --> 00:03:26.639
in the form of preprocessing to deal with dimensionality. And having a lot of variables

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:31.679
turn it into a smaller, hopefully better set of variables. But there's something very

00:03:31.679 --> 00:03:35.960
glaring right in the middle of my diagram right here that we haven't been able to do

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:43.440
for the longest time. And that's what I wanted to, that's what drove me to work on this project

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:50.199
is we want to work with clustering, but it just didn't fit in. And it wasn't even a little

00:03:50.199 --> 00:03:59.399
happy to make it work. It wasn't possible before to do any kind of clustering models.

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:06.559
That's why I'm very excited to give the first public announcement that we're introducing

00:04:06.559 --> 00:04:22.000
tidy cluster package. So, you're probably going to have a couple of questions or you're

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.920
thinking something. Yes, finally, I needed this for years. People have been asking. People

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:34.359
are trying to teach it. We have a lot of people that try to teach the classic intro to statistical

00:04:34.359 --> 00:04:41.440
machine learning and you can do almost everything in tidy models and then you have one week

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:47.559
where you show clustering and it just feels off. We're finally here. Some of you might

00:04:47.559 --> 00:04:57.519
think I really appreciate that he's dressing in the same theme as the slides. But lastly,

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:03.480
maybe more important question is why are we building another package? And this comes from

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:11.079
some internal friction, as I mentioned before, that tidy models just wasn't built to do clustering.

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:17.799
It was built with supervised models in mind. And there wasn't really any way to force it

00:05:17.799 --> 00:05:25.760
through. It just didn't work. And this is because of some fundamental differences between

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:35.119
how clustering models work and how a typical supervised models work. And the main thing,

00:05:35.119 --> 00:05:42.160
which in essence is a very fundamental property and it seems a little bit simple, but it's

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:48.320
most models have outcomes. And this is, yeah, of course they have outcomes, but it meant

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:53.679
that every single piece of code we have, more or less, is written with outcomes in

00:05:53.679 --> 00:06:01.720
mind. And it just meant that it didn't work. Like we couldn't make it work because not

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:07.720
only do clustering models not have outcomes, we don't want you to put in outcomes because

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:15.600
it will be a symptom of you're trying to do the wrong thing. We also have in tidy models

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:21.279
the idea that we have clearly defined predictions, which are then clustering, very controversial

00:06:21.279 --> 00:06:28.079
topic. We'll still talk about it, but it still is not the most clearly defined thing. And

00:06:28.079 --> 00:06:36.239
lastly, related to the idea of outcomes, having a ground truth to test your model against

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:42.880
means that you can do performance checking. You can have a model, you hide the outcome,

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:50.720
you predict on it and see, do my predictions align with the true values? That makes it

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:58.239
very easy to do normal performance metrics. We can do no such thing with clustering methods.

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:05.359
There are some ways of seeing, can we make, does this clustering model appear to be solid,

